Right-wing populists win in Austria, with a total of 29%
According to the first preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday brought a noticeable weakening of the two parties of the so far Grand Coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of the current President Wilhelm Molterer was seriously shaken, suffered a particularly strong loss.
On the other hand, the President of the Association for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the provincial magistrate of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, is preparing for a winning return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the country's strongest party remains the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) with 29.8% of the votes, but it lost 5.5 percent of the votes compared to the last elections in 2006.
The ÖVP was even worse, which lost nearly nine percent of the votes by 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both major parties in Austria's post-war history, and especially in the People's Party, which has brought early elections, the result is literally disastrous.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a significant advantage before SPÖ, according to public opinion polls.
However, the voters apparently punished him for allowing the government to fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, speculations were made about the possible resignation of party president Wilhelm Molterer and current Vice Chancellor.
Observers believe that this could take place on Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party presidency.
This development would probably facilitate the increasingly likely way out of the election result, i.e. the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP Grand Coalition.
In view of the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Austrian Freedom Party (FPÖ) had previously won 18 percent of the votes and the BZÖ had 11 percent of the votes - however, the Social Democrats expressed their fear of the repetition of 1999, when the People's Party agreed to joint government with the populists (the FPÖ was still united at the time, it was removed from the BZÖ in 2005), which even imposed sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with any party and I assume that he can return to Vienna in national politics, obviously expects this solution.
The Green Party also reached Parliament, which, however, lost some popularity and fell from third to fifth among the Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties exceeded the four percent limit and did not make it to Parliament.
