Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial effort.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed in neorenaissance style by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that's what the guidebooks say.
The building surrounds the end of the platforms with a tower at each front corner and looks like some German rural town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building's a little dwindled.
However, looking at the interior of the vaulted ticket office, it is obvious what a large-scale enterprise this was the westernmost gate.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the "late future" of conquests, with the help of this railway from Damascus to Baghdad to today's Saudi Arabia, wanted to achieve its ambitions to occupy the Middle East.
The German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
His railway lines were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
Hyderpasha Station didn't get any better.
In 1917, an ammunition train exploded and destroyed the well-developed roof of the building.
According to Turkish sources, there was a sabotage operation.
Since then, it has been slowly destroyed and history has far exceeded it.
At the same time, today, as the gateway to Anatolia and the entire eastern region, at least in a symbolic sense, it serves as Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon.
The Justice and Development Party in government - the AKP - has developed a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The new policy is marked by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, Hamas and Fatah groups in Palestine, Iraq, Iran and, of course, the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to assess the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I boarded the night train to Ankara, the Turkish capital, to visit one of the leading foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish Member of Parliament, Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours of fussing, which at the time gave me the rhythm of the famous documentary about the old world, "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is intended as a symbol of the new secular state, which turns its back on the past of Ottoman.
However, the AKP, known to have Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This caused some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern building made of stone and steel, specifically designed for this purpose - which stands in a developing suburban district, between semi-finished shopping malls and cafés. In the latter, the middle drivers in suits - both men and women - meet to make a deal early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have been suitable for a right-middle-minded politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, a tie, and I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy goal is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War has upset order,” he said.
Turkey is isolated from its hinterland.
Today, he had to turn east and west at the same time.
He couldn't choose between the two.
He had to open up in both directions.
"But is it possible that sooner or later he will be forced to choose?" I asked.
"Turkey never wanted to be at a crossroads."
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here almost mechanically repeated: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the countries surrounding the Black Sea are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as Turkey itself.
It is as if they are trying to convey the message that, figuratively speaking, all of Europe, along with Turkey, can reach Asia and the Middle East on those railway lines heading east.
When I was back at Hydarpasha Station, after another night, mostly awake, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conura, the two German gentlemen who watched this decorative structure recover 100 years ago.
How they would have been surprised to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East are now largely in the hands of Turkey.
And as I waited at the port for the ferry to take me back through the Bosphorus, it occurred to me that Turkey was once called "the sick man of Europe."
At that time, there was at least no question as to which continent would claim this exciting country.
Memories of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: Since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley, as music director of Guildford, has led the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
According to his musical plans for the part of the city, the following year he founded his wonderful youth choir, Proteus.
In principle, only those under the age of 21 could belong to the choir, but when Proteus sang its finale in 1979 - many of us were already at the end of our 20s - we simply refused to part with the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the name of the mythological shape changer) was in line with the choir's determination and ability to cope with any sheet music they put in front of him - be it a madrigal or a Messiaen piece; unaccompanied or accompanied by a grand orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often awe-inspiring and always exciting, and it was thanks to the man whose inspiration our enthusiasm for music has remained unchanged over the years.
How often Tod told us to "let the music speak on its own."
He always said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the sheet music.
So sing it."
His conductor technique has always been completely understandable and accurate, but it is never dictatorial or exaggerated.
Whatever the level of music, he always raised it.
John Frayn Turner wrote:
If there ever was a leader who should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I got to know him well in the two decades during which he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past forty or so years, I have written reviews of over 100 concerts, but it has never disappointed me, and it has often enthralled me with them.
In Tod Handley, there was greatness and modesty together, which is very rare.
He hated those conductors who, in his words, simply "galoped through the world with one or two well-known battlehorses."
Many of us will miss it.
