The "bee car" that avoids a collision
For the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has this time been inspired by nature, precisely the world of bees, for its new invention.
The Japanese company designed a robot that avoids accidents by imitating the flight of bees.
The Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C may be the first step in the development of collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center, in collaboration with the renowned Tokyo University’s Advanced Research Centre for Science and Technology, built this little robot in Japan.
Kazuhhiro Doi, Director of Technology Public Relations and Research and Development, defines the BR23C as a further extension of Nissan’s four-level safety cover.
The robot enhances the ability of the company's products to avoid collisions.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety cover.
However, the role of the bee’s complex eyes is much more important than this, with which it can see at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions. Consequently, the bee can fly undisturbed in its own personal space.
To copy the function of the complex eye, engineers designed a so-called laser range finder.
In the 180-degree field of vision before BR23C, the instrument identifies obstacles within a range of up to 2 metres, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an operation to avoid collision.
As soon as the obstacle is detected, the small robot immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid collision.
The main difference between the system and the currently available instruments is that in this case the avoidance maneuver takes place completely automatically.
If not, the robot would not be able to respond quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
In a way other than bees, the maneuver that takes place cannot be directed upwards or downwards, nor diagonally, it can only move in two dimensions and only towards the rotation of the wheels, i.e. not in an infinite direction and way, as is the case with bees.
Therefore, Nissan used a rotation function in addition to acceleration and deceleration in the robot to avoid collisions.
“This device only has to process and respond to data every few seconds.
There is no need to store data or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can operate without interruption with only a few dozen KB memory.
This may sound surprising, but it's not gigabytes, but we're not even talking about megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of a technology for immediate collision prevention, which Nissan estimates will be able to enter production cars within ten years.
The robot operates with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, it may be possible to integrate the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to reach the end goal by avoiding obstacles on the road.
