“This strategic alliance offers Morgan Stanley a great opportunity to accelerate its transformation into a bank-holding company,” explains John Mack, CEO of the U.S. Group.
Morgan Stanley approved the new status last week to diversify its activities, but at the same time it will be under the control of the Federal Reserve.
The agreement with the MUFG confirms once again that the current financial crisis demands even more caution from corporate giants listed on Wall Street.
The terms announced on Monday show that the agreement has been amended in recent days: last Monday, Morgan only announced that it would sell 20% of its shares to the Japanese company for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, we thought the share would be made up entirely of ordinary shares,” said Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG in Tokyo.
"However, due to the current market and economic situation, we wanted to minimise and avoid potential risks."
In terms of weighted average prices, MUFG pays 7% more than book value for Morgan Stanley shares.
As a result of the transaction, the yield per share decreases by about 20%.
Under the agreement, MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into ordinary shares one year later if the trading price of the latter exceeds the exchange rate by more than 50% over a specified period of time, i.e. it will increase to about $47.
Morgan Stanley thus ensures that funds from the MUFG can help you take advantage of your investment opportunities, improve your balance sheet and increase your liquid resources.
However, the group's spokesperson did not want to provide accurate information about the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following the association of MUFG, Morgan Stanley is expected to increase its Tier I solvency rate by about 15%, making it one of the best in its own sector.
Morgan said its balance sheet had "determinately" improved since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been a great ordeal for the group, as the price of its shares has fallen by half, while the cost of its insurance against non-payment risk has skyrocketed.
This cost was reduced on Monday, but it remained at a high level of around 12%.
