Rafael Correa's statement on Monday, Quito
Rebuilding the Republic in the spirit of 21st century socialism.
This is the joint plan of Hugo Chavez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
Following the pattern of his fellow presidents and friends, Correa explained his ideas for the new constitution on Sunday.
He successfully completed his mission, as 64% of voters voted yes in the referendum, according to official results, which covered 80% of the votes.
According to this, 28% of the population voted no, 7% of the votes were invalid, while 0.7% were cast unfilled by voters.
The draft Constitution required 50% + 1 vote to be adopted.
On Sunday, two polls at the polling offices exit and a count by a non-governmental organisation proved the huge superiority of the "yes" votes by 63% and 70% respectively.
Rafael Correa, by the way, spoke of the victory of his draft constitution on the night from Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution has won an overwhelming victory," he said, thanking the Ecuadorians at their governor's seat in Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As is well known, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez, Morales and Chilean President Michelle Bachelet.
According to a report by the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, the vote took place in a calm atmosphere. Its main theme was a 444-point text that summarized the principles of "new socialism" defended by the president.
The proposed constitution places state power at the service of the economy, maintaining the right of the state to "plan development" for a country that basically lives on oil extraction by foreign companies and foreign currency sent by emigrants.
The draft constitution of Correa, elected in 2006, also strengthens the power of the head of state, who can obtain a mandate for a maximum of two consecutive periods and is entitled to dissolve the Parliament.
Correa has already announced that she intends to take advantage of this opportunity and will compete again for the mandate of head of state in February 2009.
The constitution also included the freeness of health services and education. The president has already begun to introduce it in his country, which has 13.9 million inhabitants and half of the population lives below the living standard.
Finally, the Constitution prohibits the presence of foreign troops in the country, which could put an end to Quito and Washington's agreement on the use of Ecuadorian facilities as a basis for American anti-drug measures.
19 hostages freed in Chad
He was ambushed by an Egyptian commando on the kidnappers who took 11 tourists and their eight escorts hostage ten days ago.
The hostages are now in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and eight Egyptian escorts were held in the desert for ten days, from which they were transported unharmed to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
The hostages were released in Chad during the morning by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently in good condition, they arrived by plane at the al-Maza military base, which is directly connected to Cairo International Airport, around 2:30 p.m.
The hostages were forbidden to report to the press and were immediately transferred to a hospital in Maadi, Cairo’s suburbs, where they were examined.
The hostages are "healthy" and the kidnappers have "not been paid a ransom," Egyptian tourism minister Zoheir Garanna said at the airport.
The hostages were captured on September 19 at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border regions of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, where they took part in SUV safari. The group was then carried from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown hostage takers.
The group included 11 tourists (five Italian men, five German men and one Romanian woman) and eight Egyptians: two tour guides, four drivers, one border guard and director of the safari organizer Aegyptous travel agency.
According to an Egyptian security chief, a 30-member special commando arrived on two helicopters where they raided the hostage takers just before dawn.
"There was a firefight between the troops. Half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fled," said the leader who asked for his name to be silenced.
He also said that a total of 150 special troops were sent from the Lightning Brigade in Egypt to Sudan, where German and Italian commandos were added.
Italian diplomatic leader Franco Frattini, who is currently in Belgrade, stressed the role of secret agents and special Italian action groups.
“We must acknowledge that this result could not have been achieved without the professional and effective intervention of our secret service personnel and task forces,” he said.
He also denied paying a ransom for the hostages.
The previous day, the Sudanese army announced that they had intercepted an SUV on which the kidnappers were traveling during patrols. Six of them were killed (including the leader of Chad) and two were arrested.
The army claimed that the hostage takers were in contact with a rebel organization in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which was immediately refuted by the organization concerned.
