Part of Fortis bank is nationalized by Benelux governments
With partial nationalization, Benelux states help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortison, the first European to get into trouble because of the spillover effect of the U.S. credit market crisis: the three countries support the financial and insurance institution with Hungarian interests with a total of EUR 11.2 billion.
The Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments discussed the matter at the highest level at the end of the week, involving the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, Fortis Bank has the first major crisis in the wave of international money market crises for more than a year, and decisions on the bank can therefore be considered a precedent in some respects.
According to the decision made on Sunday night, all three states buy up nearly half (49%) of the bank's existing property there.
The bank will certainly sell some of its interests, including, above all, the activities purchased from ABN Amro in the Netherlands last year, mainly insurance.
Fortis shares started to fall sharply last week, and in the second half of the week there were serious crisis phenomena at the institute.
Analysts, however, agree that with 85,000 employees, the bank is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The company’s papers fell to a 14-year low by about 12 percent on Friday alone.
Since January, the value of shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
In terms of current share prices, the total market capitalisation of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the company directors, this is not realistic.
The management blamed overseas market uncertainty over the adoption of the $700 billion U.S. package plan for the fall of Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers went up slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx appointed a new CEO to head the bank.
The financial institution has also been looking for private buyers, but no one has come forward with a meaningful offer.
The Belgian government has already indicated that investors do not have to worry or lose their money.
There has been no panic among the bank's clients so far, the accounts have not been stormed.
In Hungary Fortis has an independent branch and has also acquired leasing companies.
Fox in the Henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to enter into an insurance contract with the applicant based on people’s drug purchase data.
Data protection professionals fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a data protection program that always links the use of prescription data to the consent of the person concerned.
This must be in independent hands, otherwise we will leave the henhouse to the fox," Richard Dick, the developer of the drug prescription program, said in a statement.
Insurance companies make the premium and the amount due in the event of damage dependent on the health status of the applicant client, and if they consider the risk to be too high, they do not take insurance with it.
In the past, the person was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the light of the results of the investigation.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: from pharmacies, based on the customer's identification number, he can easily obtain what medicines he has purchased in the last year and a half, and from this the program itself concludes what disease he suffers and what his health condition is.
For example, taking high doses of cholesterol on a regular basis suggests that you have virtually unmanageable high levels of blood fat, which immediately puts you in a higher risk category.
Several versions of the programme are in circulation, some also determine a risk multiplier number, so the insurance company has little to do outside of paperwork, although small difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include that some drugs can be used for several purposes, such as some compounds against migraines or heat waves, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter is a significant risk-enhancing factor for business insurers, not the former.
Separate companies have been formed to retrieve and process the data, and before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, they ask for the consent of the patient.
They are now obliged to do so by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their failure so far.
Some companies are now processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to drug consumption data, so they can provide an even more accurate picture of the health of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data, and at the same time it will be increasingly difficult to control the use.
There is a separate health data protection law, but its scope applies only to healthcare providers and insurers.
Before the Congress, there is a bill that gives the authorities control over businesses specialising in data provision.
Dick Richard admits that this is not enough: therefore, he has improved his programme, which would require the data to be transmitted to the data subject's explicit consent.
Another question is that the person concerned cannot very much refuse the consent, otherwise the insurers will not conclude a contract with him.
So the hens are somehow dependent on the fox's goodwill.
